                            <comment id="13956086" author="nekto0n" created="Tue, 1 Apr 2014 05:22:08 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Submitting a patch is no big deal. I just can&apos;t think of a test case... We could test that with non-zero initialized buffer we get right result - but there&apos;s no way to control buffer contents from outside &lt;tt&gt;pyzoo_get&lt;/tt&gt;. Could you help with the script for a test case?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13956273" author="michim" created="Tue, 1 Apr 2014 10:02:40 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Hi Nikita,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I was thinking we could have a simple test case in python (if there isn&apos;t one already) that calls &lt;tt&gt;zookeeper.get&lt;/tt&gt; on an empty znode and makes sure that it&apos;s empty. You don&apos;t need to explicitly modify the malloc&apos;ed buffer in &lt;tt&gt;pyzoo_get&lt;/tt&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13956308" author="nekto0n" created="Tue, 1 Apr 2014 10:42:07 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;I don&apos;t think it&apos;s possible to create an empty node (i.e. buff = null, size = -1) from python, we only can create node with empty string as valud (i.e. buff = &apos;&apos;, size = 0).&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13956747" author="michim" created="Tue, 1 Apr 2014 17:54:21 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Ok maybe I misunderstood the bug description. I thought doing a get on empty znode on FreeBSD sometimes returns random data. What I meant to ask was to write a python test case that reproduces the issue. It&apos;s ok if it doesn&apos;t happen on Linux, or it&apos;s not 100% reproducible on FreeBSD. &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13956897" author="nekto0n" created="Tue, 1 Apr 2014 19:52:12 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Yep, you&apos;re right. Just checked that empty node even created from python (i.e. when we pass empty string with size 0) returns with size -1.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&apos;ll attach patch in a moment...&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
